    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix memory leak in P7 reassembly queue message removal\n\n### Summary\nThe VNF P7 message reassembly queue contained a memory leak when removing completed messages from the queue. Under sustained high-throughput conditions with frequent message segmentation, this leak caused gradual memory exhaustion and eventual VNF crash.\n\nThe leak occurred because the `vnf_p7_rx_reassembly_queue_remove_msg` function was comparing message sequence numbers instead of direct pointer comparison, leading to scenarios where the wrong message structure was removed from the linked list, leaving orphaned allocations.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/vnf/src/vnf_p7.c`: Modified `vnf_p7_rx_reassembly_queue_remove_msg` to use direct pointer comparison instead of sequence number matching for message removal.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Configure VNF with high P7 message segmentation (small segment_size)\n2. Generate sustained traffic with frequent segmented messages\n3. Monitor VNF process memory usage over time\n4. Observe gradual increase in RSS until OOM conditions occur\n\nUnder lab conditions, memory usage increased by ~2-5MB/minute depending on segmentation frequency. Systems without monitoring eventually terminated with OOM killer invocation.\n\n"
}